'''Frank's sign''' or '''Frank sign''' is a diagonal ear lobe crease (ELC) extending diagonally from the [[Tragus (ear)|tragus]] across the [[lobule]] to the rear edge of the auricle.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Frank ST |title=Aural sign of coronary-artery disease |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=289 |issue=6 |pages=327–8 |year=1973 |month=August |pmid=4718047 |doi= 10.1056/NEJM197308092890622|url=}}</ref>

It has been hypothesised that Frank's sign is indicative of [[cardiovascular disease]]<ref>Miot, H.A., Molina de Medeiros, M. etal (2006). [http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?pid=S0365-05962006000100003&script=sci_arttext&tlng=en Association between coronary artery disease and the diagonal earlobe an preauricular creases in men.] Anais Brasileiros de Dermatologia. vol.81 no.1</ref> and/or [[diabetes]]. Some studies have described Frank's sign as a marker of cardiovascular disease but not linked to the severity of the condition.<ref name="pmid3827155">{{cite journal |author=Lesbre JP, Castier B, Tribouilloy C, Labeille B, Isorni C |title=[Frank's sign and coronary disease] |language=French |journal=Ann Cardiol Angeiol (Paris) |volume=36 |issue=1 |pages=37–41 |year=1987 |month=January |pmid=3827155 |doi= |url=}}</ref> In contrast, other studies have rebutted any association between Frank's sign and coronary artery disease.<ref name="pmid11108067">{{cite journal |author=Davis TM, Balme M, Jackson D, Stuccio G, Bruce DG |title=The diagonal ear lobe crease (Frank's sign) is not associated with coronary artery disease or retinopathy in type 2 diabetes: the Fremantle Diabetes Study |journal=Aust N Z J Med |volume=30 |issue=5 |pages=573–7 |year=2000 |month=October |pmid=11108067 |doi= 10.1111/j.1445-5994.2000.tb00858.x|url=}}</ref>

However, researchers{{Who|date=August 2011}} do agree that these creases have no predictive value in Native American Indian and Asian patients{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}.

Some studies have focused upon bilateral ELC.<ref name="pmid15539887">{{cite journal |author=Evrengül H, Dursunoğlu D, Kaftan A, ''et al.'' |title=Bilateral diagonal earlobe crease and coronary artery disease: a significant association |journal=Dermatology (Basel) |volume=209 |issue=4 |pages=271–5 |year=2004 |pmid=15539887 |doi=10.1159/000080847 |url=http://content.karger.com/produktedb/produkte.asp?typ=fulltext&file=DRM2004209004271}}</ref>

The sign is named after [[Sanders T. Frank|Dr. Sanders T. Frank]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Frank ST |title=Aural sign of coronary-artery disease |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=289 |issue=6 |pages=327–8 |year=1973 |month=August |pmid=4718047 |doi= 10.1056/NEJM197308092890622|url= }}</ref>

==Severity==
*Grade 3  - A deep crease across the whole of the earlobe{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}
*Grade 2a - Creased more than halfway across the earlobe{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}
*Grade 2b - A superficial crease across the earlobe{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}
*Grade 1  - A small amount of wrinkling on the earlobe{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}

